
     <p>2025.06.7 : <a href="https://ndpr.nd.edu/reviews/schopenhauers-moral-philosophy/" >View this Review Online</a> | <a href="https://ndpr.nd.edu//news" >View Recent NDPR Reviews</a></p>
     <p><strong><p><strong>Patrick Hassan (ed.), <em>Schopenhauer’s Moral Philosophy</em>, Routledge, 2022, 206pp., $54.99 (pbk), ISBN 9780367548704. </strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Sean T. Murphy, Southern Utah University</strong></p>
     <p>Consider just one of Nietzsche’s many veiled critical assessments of Schopenhauer’s—his great educator’s—ethics of compassion:</p> <p style="padding-left: 40px;">Let us reflect seriously upon this question: why do we leap after someone who has fallen into the water in front of us, even though we feel no kind of affection for him? Out of pity: at that moment we are thinking only of the other person—thus says thoughtlessness (<em>Daybreak</em> 133).</p> <p>If we factor in the tendency for such Nietzschean caricatures to constitute many first encounters with Schopenhauer’s moral philosophy, then it is no wonder that the fight to give it a proper hearing and to overcome the charge of ‘thoughtlessness’ has been an uphill battle. Thankfully, the expert contributors to this volume have plowed on undeterred. The...
